                          '  </table>\n'
                          '</div>\n'
                          '<p>For cerebellar tumors, midline lesions commonly cause truncal or gait ataxia, head '
                          'titubation, and nystagmus; lateral lesions more often cause dysmetria, intention tremor, '
                          'and heel-to-shin difficulty.</p>\n'
                          '<h3>3. General workup</h3>\n'
                          '<p>Unstable vital signs, altered mental status, or suspicion for increased intracranial '
                          'pressure—such as headache, nausea/vomiting, or papilledema—requires emergency evaluation. '
                          'Workup includes a full neurologic examination, skin examination for tumor-predisposition '
                          'syndromes, and fundoscopy for papilledema. In emergencies, non-contrast head CT can assess '
                          'hydrocephalus, impending herniation, or hemorrhage; brain MRI with and without contrast is '
