                          '      <tr><td>ATRT</td><td>50.4 Gy to primary if age &lt;3; consider 36 Gy CSI if age '
                          '&gt;3</td><td>Institution-dependent</td></tr>\n'
                          '    </tbody>\n'
                          '  </table>\n'
                          '</div>\n'
                          '<h3>5. CSI technique</h3>\n'
                          '<p>CSI simulation is usually supine with shoulders down and neck extended, minimizing '
                          'spinal curvature. A 5-point mask immobilizes the head and shoulders; the body is supported '
                          'with a large vac-loc, and a knee sponge can reduce lordosis. Contours include the whole '
                          'brain, covering the cribriform plate and crista galli, and the entire thecal sac to '
                          'approximately S1–S2 with lateral nerve-root extensions.</p>\n'
                          '<p>Fields commonly include two lateral whole-brain beams plus one or more '
                          'posterior-anterior spine fields. For multiple spine fields, the match point should be '
                          'placed anterior to the spinal cord to avoid a cord hotspot, and junctions should be '
                          'feathered regularly, commonly every 5 fractions or every 9 Gy by 0.5–1 cm.</p>\n'
                          '<h3>6. Protons versus photons for CSI</h3>\n'
                          '<p>CSI is one of the clearest pediatric settings in which protons have strong dosimetric '
